Part I - (Used Car Data Exploration)¶

by (Chika Njoku)¶

Introduction¶

About:

There is an automobile company XYZ from India which aspires to enter the Indian used-car market by setting up their company locally to give competition to their counterparts.

They want to understand the factors affecting the pricing of cars in the market, since those may be very different from the new car market. Essentially, the company wants to know: Which variables are significant in predicting the price of a used car? How well those variables describe the price of a car Based on various market surveys, the consulting firm has gathered a large dataset of different types of used cars across the market. The Dataset contains the various variables that will be useful in the analysis process, Sales_ID,name,year,selling_price,km_driven,Region,stateor Province,city,fuel,seller type,owner,mileage,engine,maxpower,seats,sold. The datset is taken from kaggle.com

x ='Fuel Types'
y='Frequency Count'


def countplot(x):
  # data setup
    plt.figure(figsize =(20,5))
    base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.countplot(data = used_car, x=x, color = base_color)

    plt.title('{} by {}' .format(x,y))
    plt.xlabel('{}'.format(x))
    plt.ylabel('{}'.format(y));
    
countplot('fuel')

Obsevation

THe Diesel has the highest frequency distribution

Insights Gained During Univariate Exploration¶

1.We have a large proprtion of the cars unsold whose value is 5906 while the sold used cars is only 2000

2.The used car names that has a higher frequency in the dataset is Maurti, Myundai,Mahindra and

Tata

3.For the Fuel, the Diesel accounts for a higer proportion of what the used cars use

4.Most of the used cars come from the central region

5.The used cars are owned more by individual owners

6.Most of the used cars the selling price are betweer the ranges of 0-200000. The distribution of the selling price is unimodal and rightly skewed .

7.Most of the used car engine are between 1200 and 1300 8.Most of the used cars were purchased more between 2012 and 2017 so that accounts why most of the cars were not sold

9.The used cars have not been driven much

10.Most of the cars are more of Manual than Automatic

The data set had no missing values ,duplicates so no cleaning was effected on it.

Due to the nature of the dataset We didnt need to carry out any other operations to clean and tidy data

The relationship between year and the mileage¶

In [40]:
# plotting a plot to show the relationship between year and mileage 
plt.figure(figsize = [20, 5])
# PLOT ON LEFT - SIMPLE SCATTER
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
sns.regplot(data = used_car, x = 'year', y = 'mileage', truncate=False);

##########################################
# PLOT ON RIGHT - SCATTER PLOT WITH JITTER
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
# truncate=True, the regression line is bounded by the data limits. 
#  truncate=False, it extends to the x axis limits.
# the x_jitter will make each x value will be adjusted randomly by +/-0.2
sns.regplot(data = used_car, x = 'year', y = 'mileage', truncate=False, x_jitter=0.2);

Obsevation

In the left scatter plot above, the degree of variability in the data and strength of the relationship is clear but the data points are not as more compactely concentrated as in the secon subplot . As we employed the jitter it clearly shows the concentration of the datapointsbetween the year 2005 and 2020 and the mileage concentrated more between 30

Conclusion¶

Among many features it can be said that Year, Name, Region are categories which affect buying and selling of car.

Fuel feature the diesel type, does predict the price of the car but it has no significat relation to its being sold and unsold

The Transmission Mode, the Manual has a high significant relation to selling price and sold than the Automatic,and thus can predict the price of the car

Mileage and Km_Driven doesn't affect price,it can be observed that cars with mileage close to 30 are being sold compared to cars with low mileage and most of the cars have not been driven for long and that could also be factor why they dont command a high price.

Most of the used_car were unsold from 1995 to 2010. From 2010 to 2020 there was an increase of sales and price

Most of the used cars are on first owner basis and this commands a high selling price compare to the others. and most of first owner basis are sold more this could be a good determing factor for price
